project_info.prj_title: Dunklee Pond Dam Removal
project_info.prj_overview: The Dunklee Pond Dam on the Tenney Brook in the City of Rutland, VT will be removed. This project entails removing the 75 ft long and 10 ft high stone rubble and concrete barrier and restoring hydrologic connectivity to Tenney Brook. A downstream fish passage weir is also proposed to address the perched concrete box culvert that is located immediately downstream under Route 7.

project_info.prj_title: 2021 River Corridor Easement Implementation: Ricketson
project_info.prj_overview: This project implements a 19.6 acre river corridor easement on the Little River watershed in Stowe. This easement will provide protection in perpetuity of a high priority river corridor to allow for passive restoration of channel stability by allowing natural erosive forces of the river to establish its least erosive form over time (i.e., equilibrium condition).

project_info.prj_title: 2021 River Corridor Easement Implementation: Sheldon and Westfield
project_info.prj_overview: This project will implement two river corridor easements. The first project is an 37.5-acre corridor project along the Missisquoi River in the town of Sheldon, and the second project is an 37-acre corridor project in the town of Westfield along the Missisquoi River. These easements will provide protection in perpetuity of a high priority river corridor to allow for passive restoration of channel stability by allowing natural erosive forces of the river to establish its least erosive form over time (i.e., equilibrium condition).

project_info.prj_title: Pelletier Dam Removal MOA 2022
project_info.prj_overview: The purpose of this project is to remove the Pelletier Dam located on Pelletier Pond in Castleton, VT. This will serve to reconnect a substantial reach of trout habitat and address sediment upstream and severe incision and erosion downstream from dam, and improve water quality.

project_info.prj_title: Camp Wihakowi Dam Removal
project_info.prj_complete_comments: In progress as of April 2021, per H. Carr (E. Beck, 30 April 2021)
project_info.prj_overview: The project removes the Camp Wihakowi Dam, an approximately 13.4-foot-high, run-of-the-river, concrete gravity structure that is founded on bedrock and classified as a low hazard. A new channel will also be created, approximating a natural stream slope with bends and curves (sinuosity). There is an estimated total of approximately 33,400 cubic yards of accumulated sediment in the reservoir due to the dam with the proposed removal of approximately 26,000 cubic yards and the balance remaining in the channel to naturally migrate to the sediment starved river sections downstream. The newly re-exposed floodplain upstream of the dam will be stabilized and planted with native species. The completed project will result in removal of the dam and restoration of a free-flowing waterway.

project_info.prj_title: 2021 WUV Clean Water Design and Implementation Block Grant- WUV
project_info.prj_complete_comments: Project is either pending or in progress, per H. Carr, 27 April 2021 (E. Beck, 30 April 2021).
project_info.prj_overview: The Clean Water Design and Implementation Block Grant agreement supports the grantee in funding projects across the state that reduce sediment and nutrient pollution from entering the states rivers, lakes, and wetlands. Various project types are implemented under this agreement in the stormwater and natural resources sectors. Project reported is a installation of stormwater retrofit at the old Numia Factory located at 197 Farrant Street in Newport, VT to reduce phosphorus and sediment loading into Lake Memphremagog. The design consists of rerouting the outflow from the existing collection basin south thru a hydrodynamic separator into a gravel wetland retention system prior to releasing into the Prouty Bay section of Lake Memphremagog.
